What is systemd in Linux?
-------------------------

-> The systemd is a system and service manager used in many modern Linux distributions to control the boot process and manage system services.

-> It is the first process started by the Linux kernel during booting and runs with Process ID (PID) 1.

-> Main Functions of systemd
----------------------------

1. System Boot Management

    systemd initializes the operating system during startup.

    It:
        starts essential services
        mounts filesystems
        prepares the system environment
        manages dependencies between services

2. Service Management

    It controls background services (daemons) such as:

        web servers
        SSH servers
        database servers
        networking services

    Example services:

        sshd
        httpd
        nginx

3. Parallel Service Startup

    Unlike older init systems, systemd can start multiple services simultaneously, which makes the boot process faster.

4. Logging Management 

    systemd includes a logging service called:

        journald

    Logs can be viewed using:

        #journalctl

-> Advantages of systemd:
-------------------------

    a. Faster boot times
    
    b. Better dependency management
    
    c. Parallel startup of services
    
    d. Centralized logging
    
    e. Easier service control
    
    f. Automatic service recovery
